6121, "span": {"begin": 757, "end": 778}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013610"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Tachycardia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999983549118042, "span": {"begin": 857, "end": 868}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9888211488723755, "span": {"begin": 891, "end": 903}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005207"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Muscle fasciculations      Twitching", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9978532195091248, "span": {"begin": 909, "end": 945}}, {"id": ["mesh:C000629404"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Flaccid paralysis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9994962215423584, "span": {"begin": 951, "end": 968}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001986"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "bronchoconstriction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999743700027466, "span": {"begin": 1093, "end": 1112}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001919"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bradycardia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999974250793457, "span": {"begin": 1114, "end": 1125}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013610"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tachycardia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998437166213989, "span": {"begin": 1130, "end": 1141}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007022"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypotension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999918937683105, "span": {"begin": 1143, "end": 1154}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999679327011108, "span": {"begin": 1159, "end": 1171}}], "text": "AChE inhibition leading to increased cholinergic signaling manifests across a range of&nbsp; &ldquo;cholinergic syndrome&rdquo; symptoms appearing as organ-type-specific responses. In cases of acute cholinergic poisoning, certain signs are often measurable within just a few minutes after exposure to an AChE inhibitor.  One of the earliest and most frequent signs of cholinergic poisoning is constricted pupils (miosis) (Wadia, 1974), which is a manifestation mediated by muscarinic cholinergic receptors. Other manifestations observed in cases of cholinergic poisoning are collectively known as SLUDGE symptoms (Peter):      Salivation      Lacrimation (tears)      Urination      Defecations      Gastric Cramps      Emesis (vomiting)     Other signs of cholinergic poisoning are mediated by nicotinic cholinergic signalling. These include (Costa):      Tachycardia,&nbsp;      Transient hypertension      Muscle fasciculations      Twitching      Flaccid paralysis     Other signs of increased cholinergic signalling occurring in the lungs and heart include increased bronchial secretion, bronchoconstriction, bradycardia and tachycardia, hypotension and hypertension (Costa, Peter).&nbsp;  This KER is focussed on the signs of increased cholinergic signalling frequently described and/or measured in laboratory, field and clinical studies.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:29:06 +0000 2026"}